                                        <p style="color: #ccc; margin-bottom: 25px;">Get an honest 30-min consultation with a senior logistics engineer. We'll help you pick the path with the lowest 5-year TCO for your shipment volume.</p>
                                        <a href="https://www.itdgrowthlabs.com/contact-us.php" style="background: #ff5722; color: #fff; padding: 14px 32px; border-radius: 6px; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; display: inline-block;">Book a Free Consultation</a>
                                    </div>

                                    <!-- FAQ Section for AEO -->
                                    <div class="faq-section" style="margin-top: 40px;">
                                        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
                                        <h3>Should I build my courier software from scratch or buy a white-label SaaS?</h3>
                                        <p>White-label wins under 3,000 shipments/day or when launching in &lt;30 days. Custom wins above that volume or when you have unique workflows or need full IP ownership. Most growing couriers use a hybrid: launch on white-label, migrate to custom by year 2.</p>
                                        <h3>How much does white-label courier software cost in 2026?</h3>
                                        <p>Typical Indian-market pricing: &#8377;6–10L year 1 (license + setup + per-shipment fees), scaling to &#8377;26–42L by year 5 as volume grows. Some platforms add per-driver, per-hub or per-API-call charges that can balloon the bill faster than expected.</p>
                                        <h3>How much does a custom courier software build cost?</h3>
                                        <p>&#8377;25–35L for a full build (driver app + dispatcher + customer app + admin dashboard) over 12–16 weeks. Year 2+ maintenance runs &#8377;15–22L/year. The 5-year TCO is similar to white-label but you own the IP at the end.</p>
                                        <h3>What's the safest migration path from white-label to custom?</h3>
                                        <p>Don't do a big-bang switch. Start by replacing one component (typically the admin dashboard or dispatcher first), run dual-write for 60 days, then progressively migrate the driver app and customer app. Most successful migrations span 4–6 months.</p>
                                        <h3>How do I avoid vendor lock-in with white-label SaaS?</h3>
                                        <p>Insist on these contract clauses from day one: monthly data exports in standard format, schema documentation, defined exit clauses, and the right to keep your customer data after termination. Many SaaS contracts make migration painful by design — read the fine print.</p>
